article.headline: Wizards open game 1-for-14 from field
article.linkText: McGrady, Magic snap six-game losing streak
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The Orlando Magic haven't had many 25-point leads in the first half. Maybe that's why they spent the rest of the game giving much of it back. Orlando ended a six-game losing streak by holding on for a 103-92 win over the Washington Wizards on Friday night. Tracy McGrady scored 35 points, 25 after halftime, to lead five players in double figures. "We had a lot of guys stepping up and playing a good, solid defense, which allowed us to create a lead," Orlando coach Johnny Davis said. "We needed every one of those points in the second half because we did not finish the game the way we would've liked to." Orlando, the NBA's worst defensive team, limited the Wizards to 11 points in the opening quarter en route to a 25-point first half. The defensive efforts were season bests in a quarter and half for the Magic, who allowed at least 60 points in the first half during every game of their skid. The Magic then returned to their complacent ways, allowing 37 points in the third quarter and 67 after the break. Washington crept within eight points with more than four minutes to play, prompting worries on the Orlando bench. "Once you get up, you have a tendency to relax a little bit," said Keith Bogans, who had 13 points and nine rebounds. "We've been on that side -- down 20 and trying to come back -- so we know what it's all about." But McGrady hit five free throws in the final 3:40 to send the Wizards to their fourth straight loss and ninth in 10 games. Washington has an eight-game road losing streak and hasn't beaten an Atlantic Division foe in nine tries. McGrady sank eight free throws, giving him a Magic-record 1,606. The previous leader was Shaquille O'Neal, who made 1,602 with Orlando. Juwan Howard added 10 points and 12 rebounds, and Lee Nailon came off the bench to score 11 points -- all in the fourth quarter. Andrew DeClercq grabbed a season-best 13 rebounds before fouling out. Larry Hughes scored 22 of his 26 points in the second half to lead Washington. Kwame Brown had 17 points, and Gilbert Arenas added 13. The Wizards opened the game by missing all but one of their first 14 shots -- including a stretch of 12 straight. In the next quarter, they made only three shots, two being 3-pointers, in 15 attempts. For the half, Washington shot 22 percent (8-for-35) and was held to two points in a span of more than 8{ minutes. By then, Orlando was up 38-13. "We wasted 20 minutes in the first half," Wizards coach Eddie Jordan said. "It was part of our doing and part of what the Magic did." As bad as the Wizards' numbers were, it was uglier to watch. Brown fired up a running jumper that barely hit the NBA logo in the corner of the backboard, while Juan Dixon had a shot blocked back into his forehead and later tossed a behind-the-back pass that hit DeClercq in the stomach 2 feet away. "It makes us seem like the worst team in the league," Brown said. "We're certainly a better team than that, and we showed it in the second half."

Game notes
Orlando reserve point guard Rod Strickland strained his left hamstring shortly before halftime and didn't return. He's listed as day-to-day. ... Arenas was called for a flagrant foul for jumping on Bogans during a layup early in the third quarter. Five minutes later, McGrady and Brendan Haywood drew double technicals for a skirmish when McGrady was fouled on a 3-pointer.... The last time the Wizards had a longer stretch of road losses was the 2000-01 season, when they lost 10 straight away from Washington.
